xdmp.httpGet("http://www.my.com/document.xhtml",
     {
       "authentication": {
         "method" : "basic",
         "username" : "myname",
         "password" : "mypassword"
       }
     })
=> the response from the server as well as the specified document

fn.subsequence(
  xdmp.httpGet("http://www.marklogic.com",
     {
       "encoding" : "iso-8859-1"
     }), 1, 2)
=> The specified document, transcoded from ISO-8859-1
   to UTF-8 encoding.  This assumes the document is
   encoded in ISO-8859-1.

xdmp:tidy( xdmp:http-get("http://www.my.com/somehtml.html")[2])[2] => The specified html document, cleaned and transformed to xhtml by xdmp:tidy. The second node of the tidy output is the xhtml node (the first node is the status). You could then perform XPath on the output to return portions of the document. Note that the document (and all of its elements) will be in the XHTML namespace, so you need to specify the namespace in the XPath steps. For example:
xquery version "1.0-ml"; declare namespace xh="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml";
xdmp:tidy( xdmp:http-get("http://www.my.com/somehtml.html")[2])[2]//xh:title

